  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA111-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viriccip peṟṟup pukaṉṟa tōḻi talaivikku uraittatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante who entered after receiving a disembodied voice said to HER.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA111">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            atta viruppaip pūvi ṉaṉṉa</l>
<l>            tuyttalai yiṟavoṭu tokaimīṉ peṟīi</l>
<l>            varivalaip paratavar karuviṉaic ciṟāar</l>
<l>            māṉmēṟ koṇṭu māṉkaṇaṅ takaimār</l>
<l>            ventiṟa liḷaiyavar vēṭṭeḻun tāṅkut </l>
<l>            timiṟmēṟ koṇṭu tiraiccura nīnti</l>
<l>            vāḷvāyc cuṟavoṭu vayamīṉ keṇṭi</l>
<l>            niṇampey tōṇiya rikumaṇa liḻitarum</l>
<l>            peruṅkaḻip pākkaṅ kalleṉa</l>
<l>            varumē tōḻi koṇkaṉ ṟērē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The chariot of the man from the sea is coming, friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">noisily, to the village by the great backwaters,</l>
<l rend="indent">where after mounting the boats [and] crossing the desert of waves,</l>
<l rend="indent3">the boatsmen descend on the sand, cutting the strong fish</l>
<l rend="indent3">along with the swordfish(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vāḷ vāy cuṟa</term>: here it is possible to read a metaphor for the sharpness of the shark's teeth, or a specification of the fish as a swordfish (which is the traditional interpretation).</note> [and] pouring fat,</l>
<l rend="indent4">as if youths of hot strength in order to seize groups of deer,</l>
<l rend="indent4">had risen for the hunt mounted on [their] horses(?)<note place="foot">The comparison makes sense only if the point is the parallelism between the youths on land who are hunting on horseback and the youths of the sea who ride their boats, as is also suggested by the parallel construction <term xml:lang="ta">māṉ mēṟkoṇṭu - timiḷ mēṟkoṇṭu</term>.</note></l>
<l>– the children with sombre work of the fishermen with lined<note place="foot">T.V.G. takes <term xml:lang="ta">vari</term> here to mean well-made.</note> nets,</l>
<l>obtaining fish in masses together with soft-headed prawns,</l>
<l rend="indent4">as the flowers of the Iruppai tree by the road.<note place="foot">The first three lines are puzzling since they are redundant and add in no way to what follows in the poem. Are they placed correctly?</note></l>
        </lg>
         </div>
